File: `platform/cli/src/commands/stop.ts`

Root cause: The health validation fix in v0.0.38 added a check at line ~93: `typeof data.status === 'string' && typeof data.version === 'string'`. But the unauthenticated /health endpoint returns only `{"status":"ok"}` without the `version` field. The `stop` command at line ~90 calls `fetch(url, { signal: ... })` WITHOUT an Authorization header.

Fix: Import `readAuthSecret` from `../config.js` (like `status.ts` does at line 5). Before the fetch call at line ~90, read the auth secret and add it as an Authorization header:
```typescript
const secret = await readAuthSecret();
const headers: Record<string, string> = {};
if (secret) headers['Authorization'] = `Bearer ${secret}`;
const res = await fetch(url, { headers, signal: AbortSignal.timeout(3_000) });
```

This matches the pattern used in `status.ts` at lines 75-81. With the auth header, the /health endpoint returns the full response including `version`, and the validation passes correctly.

Compare `status.ts` lines 75-81 for the reference pattern.

File: `platform/cli/src/commands/config.ts`

The issue is in `handleConfigShow` (line ~38). When normalizing the config, missing keys are spread after the original config:
```typescript
const normalized = { localPlugins: [], tools: {}, browserToolPolicy: {}, ...config };
```
This puts `browserToolPolicy` BEFORE `config`'s keys, but JavaScript spread preserves the order of the first occurrence — so if `config` already has `localPlugins` and `tools`, those come first from `config`, then `browserToolPolicy` comes from the defaults.

The fix: Put the defaults FIRST in the spread, so they define the key order, then spread `config` to override values:
```typescript
const normalized = { localPlugins: [], tools: {}, browserToolPolicy: {}, permissions: {}, ...config };
```
Wait — this won't work because `...config` will add keys in config's order after the defaults.

Better fix: Define the explicit key order and iterate in that order instead of using `Object.entries(normalized)`. Create a `CONFIG_DISPLAY_ORDER` array and iterate through it:
```typescript
const displayOrder = ['localPlugins', 'tools', 'browserToolPolicy', 'permissions'] as const;
for (const key of displayOrder) {
  const value = normalized[key];
  // ... render
}
```
This ensures consistent ordering regardless of which keys were in the original file. Check the existing rendering logic at line ~76 which uses `for (const [key, value] of Object.entries(config))` — replace this with the ordered iteration.
